			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: [WoW] Talents &amp; Auction House System w/Comments<a name="53978"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 27 04 3:26 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The problems I have with EQ2 right now (from previews) is two-fold. First of all it seems incredible to me that none of the 'second generation' MMORPGs seem to be able to improve the mob Ai to any great extent. EQ2 has advertised this inability by promising us anti-kiting code. In essence this means that the mobs in EQ2 will be precisely the same as in EQ, the only differences will be from the class types and a mindless zombie will be as intelligent as an arch-sorceror or a dragon.
<br />

<br />
My other big issue with EQ2 is that are adopting a DAoC-like buff system. Buffs have no durations but require the buffer to be within the (still) 6-character group. In essence what this means is that power-gamers will simply employ buffbot accounts. This is one of the issues that led me to giving up DAoC.
<br />

<br />
I actually have great difficulty in seeing where EQ2's audience is going to come from. The 'casual' MMORPG market is pretty busy right now. CoH is a recent example of a game that caters excellently to players who want to play for short periods and do not mind fairly monotonous game-play. This is precisely the group that EQ2 is aiming for, and EQ2 has so far shown very little that puts it above the crowd.
<br />

<br />
By the same token WoW is amazingly similar (coincidence ya think?) in many ways. They advertise themselves as catering to the casual player, with the usual mix of incredibly bland classes and abilities. What precisely does WoW have for anyone to get excited about?
<br />

<br />
I have recently run through the crop of MMORPG offerings and I have to say I find them incredibly poor. There are very few truly original concepts out there, and where there is a spark it is drowned in something else I prefer to avoid such as PvP.
<br />

<br />
The game that is needed to blow the current set out of the water is one that offers truly intelligent mob AI. A zombie will be slow and stupid, whilst an ancient dragon should be incredibly intelligent. Adding some extra realism in this way does not make kiting impossible, it just means that the majority of mobs out there are going to be too fast or too 'intelligent' to allow it.
<br />

<br />
Right now in any MMORPG you can pretty much know precisely what a mob is going to do at any given time. Yes casters add a little variety, but even here you can predict within a spell or 2. To avoid gameplay monotany we need mobs that react to situations differently. I believe that is the future. I'm just waiting for a company to agree with me and release something that offers mobs of this nature combined with challenging, tactically complex gameplay. And I am sure I am not the only player out there in the same aufience.
<br />

<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />   Zel  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
